<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1872-05-17T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1872-05-17T00:00:00-05:00" n="189" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d189">
                        <head>No. 54.<lb/><hi rend="italic">Earl <persName type="from">Granville</persName> to Sir <persName type="to">E.
                                    Thornton</persName>.</hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Foreign
                                        Office</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1872-05-17"><hi rend="italic">May</hi> 17,
                                1872</date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p rend="center">[From British Blue Book “North America,” No. 9, (1872,) p.
                            21.]</p>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have received your dispatch of the 30th
                            ultimo, reporting your conversation with Mr. Fish on the subject of the
                            indirect claims; and, in reply, I have to acquaint you that Her
                            Majesty’s Government approve’ your guarded language on this subject, as
                            reported in your dispatch.</p>
                        <p>I am, &amp;c.,</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>GRANVILLE.</signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>